The paper deals with the computational complexity of the longest common subsequence problem, which is a fundamental problem in computer science and has been extensively studied. The paper uses the lens of fine-grained complexity to study the multivariate complexity of the problem, taking into account various input parameters. This suggests that the paper is likely to be classified under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms), cs.CC (Computational Complexity), cs.CG (Computational Geometry), cs.DM (Discrete Mathematics), and cs.LG (Machine Learning).
